'''''Uvularia puberula''''', the '''mountain bellwort''', is a plant species native to the eastern United States. It is common across [[Virginia]], [[North Carolina|North]] and [[South Carolina]], [[West Virginia]], and adjacent parts of northern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], eastern [[Tennessee]], eastern [[Kentucky]] and southern [[Pennsylvania]]. Isolated populations have been found in southern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], northern [[Alabama]], southern [[New Jersey]], and [[Long Island]] in [[New York State]].<ref>{{BONAP|ref |genus=Uvularia |species=puberula}}</ref>

''Uvularia puberula'' is a perennial herb with 1-3 pale yellow flowers per stem.<ref>{{eFloras|1|242102042|Uvularia puberula |family=Liliaceae |first1=Frederick H. |last1=Utech |first2=Shoichi |last2=Kawano}}</ref>

